text: 3 months before my wedding in june 2017 i was almost raped at a party. it took everything from me. i went into severe depression and coped with it the only way i knew how....i ate.... it was the hardest thing to pull myself out of. i was blamed for what happened. rumours were spread about me from people i thought were my friends and my own blood said i asked for it. my sister said it wasnt a big deal because "nothing happened".....this literally almost broke me. ğŸ˜­ i ate, and ate, and ate..... the next thing i knew my wedding was 3 weeks away and i was a whopping 260 pounds!!! i cried trying to put my dress on and it wouldnt lace up. i broke all over again..... i did a quick fix diet in order to fit into my dress....my wedding day came and it was the greatest day of my life, but i didnt feel great.... my dress just fit....but barely.... at some point between then and now, i decided that i would not let this predator have any more power over me. i would continue to be exactly who i was and who i was meant to be. but i later realized that i couldnt do that, it wasnt possible. i was forever changed because of this horrific event in my life. i had to come to terms with knowing that i became a statistic....i became the girl i said i would never be. i became the girl that maybe i was meant to be? but i became strong! i had to empower myself and show that i was not afraid. i would no longer let this event ruin my life. i would learn from it, be open about it, and i would move forward. â¤â¤ since then i have found out that i have a tumour growing on my liver...i had to change my life. i changed the way i ate. i started being more active outdoors. i found that being outdoors on my territory really helped me heal from my trauma. there really is something significant about land based healing. i feel so connected to everything.... anyways back to the point.... i am now 219 pounds! i reclaimed my powerğŸ’ªğŸ¾ i no longer live in fear. and now my body is benefitting from my changes. #mystory #transformation #weightloss #rape #notyourvictim #reclaimyourpower #girlpower #changes #traditionalhealing #loseweight #transformationthursday #wedding #bride #tellmeyourstory #health #metoo

#janetjackson called for an end to gender inequality during a powerful speech at the mtv european music awards on sunday night.

the pop icon, 52, delivered an emotional speech which appeared to subtly reference the #metoo movement as she accepted the honour for global icon.

making a call for global tolerance, janet chose not to reflect on her remarkable career and instead used her platform to stand up for women around the world. 
she said: â€œi feel moved to speak for womenâ€™s voices who have been stifled. â€œi am one of those women, women who have been gagged, both literally and emotionally, women who have been abused, women who have been intimidated, women who have lived in fear. â€œi stand with you. you are my sisters.â€

text:
â¤ï¸ğŸ· the short film about two fourteenyear old friends johnny and romi took us all back to the beautiful crashing-with-own-identity times of period lectures, sleazy gym teachers, times of not seeing that thereâ€™re only boys in bands and times of trying to find yourself in the sea (pool) of gender strereotypes. oh, to be a girlâ€¦ oh, to be a fourteen yearold girl! omg! how to be a girl, a human, a drummer, a rebel at the same time? how to have an â€œmâ€ and also .. not have it?

the film came to life as my graduation project studying directing. i was both theoretically and practically examining the topic of â€œgirls in filmâ€. how many of us are there behind the camera. how many of us are on the screen. who looks at us - how, and why. i was going through answers and questions and coming to confrontations and ugly statistics. and while doing that i was putting together a script about johnny, who is trying to figure out what to do with her girly fate, what it means to her, whether she should refuse it or embrace it, find herself the right role models.. it made me see the importance of speaking about female experience - first handed!

itâ€™s not a coincidence that the crew of â€œmâ€ was mostly a girl crew. once you start crying about statistics thereâ€™s not much more to do than make them better. shout out to our amazing dop liza @25hthebeat , production manager @alexkaposova, assistant director @il_kowalczuk, music couch karolina uhercikova and her girl rock band in-sane, to denisa uherova for sound postpro and andrej osvald for sound recording and @kelusko for editing. thank you the whole amazing cast who blew us away at the auditions that left me with material to write 100 more stories and funny dialogues about being yourself and being a girl.

text:
eighth week of ywam bridges of life: one thing dts in saint hippo, france ğŸ‡«ğŸ‡· - coming back to the tranquility of the base wasn't easy. neither was this week. but it does have a happy ending! our course was "warfare worship" taught by our very own school director ruth provis and interpreted into french by barbara the francophone swiss. we learned about the different types of biblical praises and worships.

i was challenged in many areas of my life. i used to genuinely worship only when i was in the mood but i realized that worship is for god. it didn't matter how i feel. he's worthy of it whether i'm happy or sad. then god challenged me to dig deeper into my past to free me from the chains of hurt that kept me bound up most of my life. with the help of a couple of school leaders, i was able to find freedom in forgiveness and experience joy from within for the first time. i'm free now and able to continue my process of full healing.

finances has been the last area of challenge for me. i'm happy to say that my lecture phase of the school (first three months of instruction) is fully paid off and i'll be graduating from the first section! the second three months of outreach phase (where students serve on a missionary trip to another country) is in jeopardy. i need 3000â‚¬ within the week to go, among other non-monetary needs. i'm trusting in god about my future no matter what. i know he'll provide for every step of the way! if you feel led to contribute to my trip to africa, please contact me. if i don't end up going however, it's not the end of the road! pray with me please.

as god brought up these areas to deal with, i felt his guidance and comfort. i grew so much and healed from a lot. i've also spent a lot of time with friends here at the school, both students and staff, playing football, going to church, or spending late nights talking about our lives with one another. i can't get over how blessed i am ğŸ˜š
name: The Travels of a Missionary

text:
v for vendetta (3/8) "remember, remember, the 5th of november..."
as the world is going towards a direction that seems to speak only words of hate, that seems to have as its one and only purpose to strip away human rights from as many people as possible, and as we approach here in new york an election day that feels as crucial as it ever has, i feel like sharing this old monologue i recorded from v for vendetta.
because only love can make us fearless. and if we don't learn to love each other, to protect each other, to support and have hope for each other, even for those we don't know, there will be no tomorrow, no hope, and no light to beak through these dark, dark days.
and, once again: for all the times i've been told to "mind my own business", because "what's an actor to do with politics?", to be careful, because "you don't want to take sides", for all the times they tried to shut me up because "these angry women are hateful and unattractive", for all the times i've been told to "go back to my country", for all this and more, tomorrow november 6th go vote.
and you know what? as a human being, a citizen, an immigrant, as a woman and as an artist, as a free person and an activist, this is exactly my own business and i will keep minding that. and no, i won't stop taking sides. i will keep choosing what to give my voice to, and if you don't agree with it, fine. but you won't shut my mouth, you won't stop my song if freedom with your words of hatred.

text:
superheroes that live among us...
.
.
when i was little i thought heroes wore masks and had capes and had some super-human strength.  when i was a teenager i thought heroes were movie stars, ball-players, or music icons.  when i was a young man i thought heroes made speeches before thousands of people...inspiring change to millions all over the world.  now i know that heroes are like the staff and volunteers of @elawc (east los angeles womenâ€™s center). .
.

[oct 10 2017 - nov 8 2018] .

within a week of jupiter into scorpio, alyssa milano (sag + sag rising!!) released the first #metoo tweet, encouraging victims of sexual abuse to come forward (following an accusation against harvey weinstein)

a seemingly trivial week in the media turned into a year-long soap opera (in scorpio taste), exposing a group of sexual abusers â€” majority of which came from some position of powerrr â€”> pluto in capricorn

as more & more people came forward with secrets that had long been buried (â™ï¸) it proved daunting for some of the most well-known names in entertainment, sports & politics.
by the 1st anniversary of metoo, 19 million victims had shared the hashtag â™¡ .

slow-orbiting neptune in pisces, made the magical 120Â° aspect to jupiter. that wave of sympathy & virtue pushed refinement of our sense of justice & collectively invited more compassion into our space. .

note that scorpioâ€™s ruler pluto, also slow-moving, consistently pushed that cap energy via the creative 60Â° aspect. .
saturn, another planet on its divine throne, has been in capricorn too, repeating issues even saturn itself can't escape the consequences of â€” like oppression, sexism, elitism, extremism, greed, & selfishness. .
too many institutions/powerful people wielded an excess of power, while clinging to outdated convictions at the expense of many. as a result, & although the movement has been building for decades, a wave of oppressed groups began speaking out in resistance
.
this points to the â€œgreat awakener" who earlier in the year changed signs into taurus & made a 120Â° trine to saturn. ego-motivated desires to preserve precedent over morality/innovation needed deconstruction (â™„) & advancement (â™…)
.
a web of energetic hierarchies exists in these underlying planetary currents. by breaking it down, we can better understand the narrative of the cosmos ğŸ’«
.
on november 8, jupiter will move into itâ€™s own sagittarius.
wonder what the next chapter holds. do you feel a change in the wind? â™¡

text:
i was born blessed/cursed with a bleeding heart, an anxious mind, a restless soul, and justice in my bones. for the last 3 years my heart has been breaking open for the marginalized and oppressed, for the victims of blinding hate and white-hot violence. my mind has been clutched by a desire to be well, and love well, while fear explodes as events play out on the global and national stage. my soul groans to be a conduit through which freedom, beauty, truth, and love flows. my bones feel the brittleness set in. (this ones not entirely metaphorical considering i just had a hysterectomy and have been off my hormone replacement therapy for 4 months.) but figuratively, i grieve how porous the idea of justice appears in the country that i love.

i donâ€™t know how the midterms play out. but i know that my faith informs my ethics, which informs my politics. and i intend to vote. 
i know i will choose to listen to my entire body and pray my hands and feet continue to push me in the direction of love when my heart breaks, my mind is at war, my soul grieves, and my bones splinter.  vote. 
follow @johnpavlovitz @rachelheldevans @theliturgists

.
.

text:
let's talk .... let's talk about body shaming and how we all body shame literally every other person we see.
whenever we see a thin or a fat person our eyes roll and our lips start chanting the words.....look at her or him...
so skinny or so huge...
the person receiving these comments not only try to ignore them but would like to punch us on our faces telling us to "fuck off". it destroys their inner peace their mental strength to face any argument about their body. telling girls about their small or huge breast size. telling boys to have huge muscles be masculine. and constantly pissing them on the way they look in any particular clothing style. 
the comments people receive are...
" khana nhi milta tereko "
" maa baap se bol protein drinks pilaye "
" hawa m udd jaaoge "
" fat ass "
" saare grh ka rashan tu hi khaate h "
" kyu dharti pr bojh bada re ho "
" gym join krne ka socha h "...
...and this list will never end.

we all are the body shamers of each other,  not accepting others because of their size and weight. you are way to skinny or lean or thin or huge or fat. this is the reality we all try to face and then we become a part of it by trying to shame the other person whose body shape and size is different from us. people receive many comments about their body not only from friends or relatives but their parents also not knowingly shame them in one way or the other.....i don't know how to end this but for sure changing yourself if you don't want to is not an option. but be yourself and dab on them people who will try to ruin your day by telling you about your body.
close your ears and eyes to such hate and negativity. and stop shaming other people. let the people know how negative it is for them to shame others their mental growth is restricted when they shame others and the ones who receive such comments about their body. 
let's accept each other with not only open arms but hearts and mind too. healthy life is what all want and if a person is mentally and physically healthy he is doing great in his life.

#mentalhealth #metoo
#physique
#comment4comment #bodyshaming #redheadwayfarer 
#realityhigh #negativity #overcome 
captured by : @capturevibes_

text:
we are changing everyday maybe every minute and for most of us it is hard to accept the changes that are going on within us. we feel uncomfortable and this change makes us angry. the change in our attitude and behaviour is not normal for us to accept and the people around us also find it difficult to deal with. these mood swings are hard to describe and harder to deal with but these are the reason behind our every effort to become a better person better than we already are. it's exhausting how we deal with our emotions every single day. not shouting out loud the things we want to speak and holding on a smile when you just want to cry to feel those powerful emotions running in your body like a current. sometimes, we let these emotional changes pile up and when they burst up we are not able to tame them and we fall into the trap of emotional distress.
main question now is....
why we feel what we feel?
we being the warriors that we are try to face everything that the day put in our way but one or the other hurdle that we face hit the most sensitive part of the shield that is protecting us and it makes us weak. and at that point we lose control and drown into the pain that we were fighting all day.
and it's completely normal and we are powerful than this and we are proud of ourselves. .
_Ã—_Ã—_Ã—_Ã—_Ã—_Ã—_Ã—_Ã—
plus: no one can tell us what we should wear, we'll wear whatever we want to whether it be a bodycon dress or skirt or suit or a saree it's our choice and our decision to make. we won't look down our balcony and listen to the baseless comments regarding our dress code that people think are going to make.
so, thank you but we are here live a life not to waste one.
and i nominate @_deep_soni12

text:
â€œon november 6, americans will head to the polls to cast a vote in one of the most important elections in a generation. each election year, americans hear stories concerning various tactics used to suppress the votes of american citizensâ€”particularly communities of colorâ€”such as strict voter id requirements, poll closures, reduced voting hours, and voter purges.1 discussed less frequently, however, are the unique barriers to voting experienced by survivors of intimate partner violence.2 according to the national resource center on domestic violence, â€œthe #1thing you can do to address domestic and sexual violence is commit to voting.â€3 unfortunately, survivors of intimate partner violence may be unable to make their voices heard in november due to barriers in the voting process, including fear of potential retaliation, privacy concerns, and lack of important election information.
studies on domestic violenceâ€™s impact on voting trends are sparse, and more research is needed to fully explore the ramifications of intimate partner violence in this area. this is due, at least in part, to the inherent difficulties of studying domestic violence generally, let alone in a specific context such as voting and elections.4 as described by isabel ruizâ€pÃ©rez, juncal plazaolaâ€castaÃ±o, and carmen vivesâ€cases, who research domestic violence as a public health problem, â€œobtaining reliable data on this type of violence is a complex task, because of the methodological issues derived from the very nature of the phenomenon, such as the private, intimate context in which this violence often takes place, which means the problem cannot be directly observed.â€5 however, a number of survivors have spoken publicly about how election processes, such as voter registration, deter them from participating in elections.6 and according to a study by the united nations, â€œthe extent of election related domestic violence in all its forms, including physical violence, is currently undocumented but believed to be substantial.â€ â€¢
â€¢
â€¢

text:
v for vendetta (1/8) "remember, remember, the 5th of november..."
as the world is going towards a direction that seems to speak only words of hate, that seems to have as its one and only purpose to strip away human rights from as many people as possible, and as we approach here in new york an election day that feels as crucial as it ever has, i feel like sharing this old monologue i recorded from v for vendetta.
because only love can make us fearless. and if we don't learn to love each other, to protect each other, to support and have hope for each other, even for those we don't know, there will be no tomorrow, no hope, and no light to beak through these dark, dark days.
and, once again: for all the times i've been told to "mind my own business", because "what's an actor to do with politics?", to be careful, because "you don't want to take sides", for all the times they tried to shut me up because "these angry women are hateful and unattractive", for all the times i've been told to "go back to my country", for all this and more, tomorrow november 6th go vote.
and you know what? as a human being, a citizen, an immigrant, as a woman and as an artist, as a free person and an activist, this is exactly my own business and i will keep minding that. and no, i won't stop taking sides. i will keep choosing what to give my voice to, and if you don't agree with it, fine. but you won't shut my mouth, you won't stop my song if freedom with your words of hatred.

as the world is going towards a direction that seems to speak only words of hate, that seems to have as its one and only purpose to strip away human rights from as many people as possible, and as we approach here in new york an election day that feels as crucial as it ever has, i feel like sharing this old monologue i recorded from v for vendetta.
because only love can make us fearless. and if we do not learn to love each other, to protect each other, to suppo and have hope for each other, even for those we do not know, there will be no tomorrow, no hope, and no light to beak through these dark, dark days.
and, once again: for all the times i have been told to "mind my own business", because "what's an actor to do with politics?", to be careful, because "you do not want to take sides", for all the times they tried to shut me up because "these angry women are hateful and unattractive", for all the times i have been told to "go back to my country", for all this and more, tomorrow november 6th go vote.
and you know what? as a human being, a citizen, an immigrant, as a woman and as an aist, as a free person and an activist, this is exactly my own business and i will keep minding that. and no, i will not stop taking sides. i will keep choosing what to give my voice to, and if you do not agree with it, fine. but you will not shut my mouth, you will not stop my song if freedom with your words of hatred.
  girlfromtheislandinnewyork

millions of peopleâ€™s personal information was stolen and used to target them in ways they wouldnâ€™t have seen, and couldnâ€™t have known about, by a mercenary outfit, cambridge analytica, who, wylie says, â€œwould work for anyoneâ€. who would pitch to russian oil companies. would they subvert elections abroad on behalf of foreign governments?

it occurs to me to ask wylie this one night. - yes.

nato or non-nato? - either. i mean theyâ€™re mercenaries. theyâ€™ll work for pretty much anyone who pays.

text:
bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn

text:
bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn

it occurs to me to ask wylie this one night. - yes.

nato or non-nato? - either. i mean theyâ€™re mercenaries. theyâ€™ll work for pretty much anyone who pays.

itâ€™s an incredible revelation. it also encapsulates all of the problems of outsourcing â€“ at a global scale, with added cyberweapons. and in the middle of it all are the public â€“ our intimate family connections, our â€œlikesâ€, our crumbs of personal data, all sucked into a swirling black hole thatâ€™s expanding and growing and is now owned by a politically motivated billionaire.

text:
- bannon got it immediately. he believes in the whole andrew breitbart doctrine that politics is downstream from culture, so to change politics you need to change culture. and fashion trends are a useful proxy for that. trump is like a pair of uggs, or crocs, basically. so how do you get from people thinking â€˜ugh. totally uglyâ€™ to the moment when everyone is wearing them? that was the inflection point he was looking for.

is what cambridge analytica does akin to bullying? - i think itâ€™s worse than bullying, christopher wylie says. - because people donâ€™t necessarily know itâ€™s being done to them. at least bullying respects the agency of people because they know. so itâ€™s worse, because if you do not respect the agency of people, anything that youâ€™re doing after that point is not conducive to a democracy. and fundamentally, information warfare is not conducive to democracy.

millions of peopleâ€™s personal information was stolen and used to target them in ways they wouldnâ€™t have seen, and couldnâ€™t have known about, by a mercenary outfit, cambridge analytica, who, wylie says, â€œwould work for anyoneâ€. who would pitch to russian oil companies. would they subvert elections abroad on behalf of foreign governments?

it occurs to me to ask wylie this one night. - yes.

nato or non-nato? - either. i mean theyâ€™re mercenaries. theyâ€™ll work for pretty much anyone who pays.

itâ€™s an incredible revelation. it also encapsulates all of the problems of outsourcing â€“ at a global scale, with added cyberweapons. and in the middle of it all are the public â€“ our intimate family connections, our â€œlikesâ€, our crumbs of personal data, all sucked into a swirling black hole thatâ€™s expanding and growing and is now owned by a politically motivated billionaire.

carole cadwalladr
the guardian

a complete run of this second wave radical feminist tabloid co-edited by kathie sarachild and barbara leon. the paper emerged from the dissolution of the redstockings, of which sarachild and leon had been members and was an important source of feminist analysis during this period (and a consequential primary source for current feminist analysis). besides sarachild and leon, prominent feminists such as shulamith firestone, colette price, carol hanisch, florence rush & patricia lawrence contributed lengthy articles on abortion, prostitution, pornography, race, the catholic church, class, consciousness-raising, etc. the paper also provides an important look at the internecine conflicts within the nyc feminist milieu, which included both direct actionist and consciousness-raising groups such as new york radical women, cell 16/the feminists, redstockings, womanâ€™s world, red womenâ€™s detachment, etc. #secondwavefeminism #womansworld #women #feminist #metoo #queer #lgbtq #periodical #kathiesarachild #redstockings #feminism #analysis

text: with everything that's gone on in my life, with all of the horror, you would think that i would be a crying and anxious mess all of the time. i will not give my abusers power over me like that. i will never stop trying to be everything that those awful people said i would never be. i will never stop being kind or polite. i will never lose hope, and i will never ever be someone i'm not. i lost everything over and over. i lost my dignity...no, they took my dignity. they took my sanity, my health, my happiness, my everything. today i wake up singing because i am grateful to be alive one more day...because it's another day that i have to repair the relationships with my children and family. it's another day that i get to prove that no matter what i have been through, i refuse to surrender to the past. i refuse to be another statistic that ends up dead from an overdose. i refuse to let anyone tell me who i am or what i stand for. i am a beautiful child of god. i am a woman of dignity and grace. i am hopefully a beacon of hope to show others that have been a victim of domestic abuse, sexual assault, or any other terrible act that it is possible to find happiness and love of self. if i wake up bitter...if i wake up and let the emotion of the terror control me...they win. today, and every day, i win. today i have god on my side and wonderful people that love me, and today i will press on, knowing that the truth is always the truth, and god will not let me suffer. #speakyourtruth #spiritualbadass #littlebutfierce #neveragain #metoo

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

text:
bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn

text:
iâ€™ve been quiet for awhile but iâ€™ve been busy behind the scenes, changing and growing and becoming empowered and i donâ€™t think iâ€™m the only one. 
i've been seeing a lot of posts about women finally verbalising their needs and how it's affecting a lot of relationships at the moment so i don't think itâ€™s unusual. i think there's a collective consciousness shifting. 
it's just my opinion but i think it has to do with shifting the patriarchy. since the #metoo campaign thereâ€™s been a shift in many of us collectively. to change things on a global level we have to be able to shift things in our own lives first. 
breaking down the foundations of our relationships and rebuilding them is what is required. sometimes it's easier to walk away because this is hard work, fighting for better but it will be better when we get through this. sometimes itâ€™s necessary to walk away but not always, sometimes itâ€™s best to stay and do the work. 
each time we stand up for our needs, our wants and our safety we change the belief that weâ€™re worth it, we are enough, we deserve better. we each must do this on an individual basis so that we reach critical mass and then we will affect change on a global basis.
breaking down the shaky foundations of our relationships and rebuilding them stronger than ever is a huge part of bringing down the patriarchy.

text:
this perpetual state of overcast and rain feels much like what a giant pause button on life would create in nature.
.
and yet, the leaves continue to fall
and the days continue to pass.
.
.
i'm learning a lot about myself these days.
a lot of things that i will presently reflect on quietly with myself and my pages.
.
and once this time has passed and it's no longer immediately relevant, it seems that will be the time i actually share so you know you are not alone in your journey.
.
but why must we wait to share those things that are happening now that burn through our souls?
.
why is it so scary to let others into anything that is non-awesome in the right-here-right-now?
.
i am learning so much these days.
.
like how the universe gives you what you ask for.
<every.single.time>
like how you must be careful what you wish for.
<every.single.time>
like how you must not lose yourself.
<every.single.time>
.

text:
i just spoke to a group of girls who when asked if they planned on voting, they said no because "it's too much work to do the research on what certain candidates position's are".
.
listen, we get that elections can be overwhelming. between the crazy political ads on tv and radio, the phone calls and having school and work already stressing you out and taking up your time and energy.
.
but there's something you can do instead of just saying no to voting. if you are registered to vote, head to the #oaklandcenter  the next time you need a break or a bite to eat, and pick up the #voterguide for the 2018 general midterm election. it is a #nonpartisan guide to what each candidate stands for and what positions they are running on. you can even take it into the votingbooth with you tomorrow!!
.
you can write on it and circle who you're voting for! it's an easy and fast way to understand who has your values and especially #equality in mind.
.
so #tomorrow #november6 instead if staying home, #getoutandvote! #vote for what you believe in, who you feel will stand up for you and #votefeminist for #womensequality and  #womensrights
.
#oaklanduniversity #ou #metoo #women #femalevote #feminism #feminist #feministvote

text:
bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn

if you put shame in a petri dish, it needs 3 things to grow - secrecy, silence and judgement. .

the two most powerful words when we are in struggle - me too". .

text:
bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn

as part of @movember iâ€™m dedicating this week to the 8 themes of my research into male teenagers mental health. the first one is the overarching theme in all my work (as you will soon see!) patriarchal or traditional masculinity.
+
there is no singular definition for what a man is, but the ideal of masculinity has been handed down over the centuries. think about itâ€¦21st century socialised gender roles and masculine ideology has been shaped through archaic times from hunter-gatherers, viking raids, norman conquests, victorian dogmas, industrial revolutions, world wars, cold wars and decades of conservative rule.
+
itâ€™s little surprise then that traditional, patriarchal masculinity highly values traits like strength, dominance, power, independence, aggression and stoicism.
+
these qualities are hopelessly out of date, but still potent. we are governed by societyâ€™s rules and gender stereotypes. dare to deviate. dare to be different. dare to rebel. and you will find yourself at the sharp end of the patriarchyâ€™s contempt.
+
â€œman up.â€ â€œbig boys donâ€™t cry.â€ â€œboys will be boysâ€ - are all a product of patriarchal masculinity, all are useless, all are harmful and all, thankfully, are our responsibility to change.
+
a new direction is needed to create a healthy masculinity by identifying the personal qualities that empower males to improve themselves, their families and society.
+
what qualities do you think makes a healthy masculinity? i would love to hear your thoughts!
+

text:
| [don't] look at me | Â© marinka massÃ©us photography 2018
â€¢
â€¢
project reflecting on a woman's wish to be seen and her simultaneous impulse to hide herself, after centuries of misogynistic programming.

for centuries, women have been reduced solely to their appearance, their physical beauty deemed their only worth. western philosophers who have shaped our collective thinking -Â aristotle[i], socrates[ii], jean-jacques rousseau[iii], darwin[iv], schopenhauer[v], nietzsche[vi] -Â compared women to animals, incapable of rational thought, devoid of intelligence. and although present generations are desperately trying to escape these narrow confinements, the ingrained programming leaves many women struggling with their self-worth.

the objectification of the female body is an effective form of dehumanization. women's sexuality is exploited and suppressed at the same time. admired and reviled, chased and judged, praised and ridiculed, all at the same time.Â this opppresive societal schizophrenia is mirrored in every woman's soul.

this series reflects on the desire to be seen, coupled with the shame and instinctive need to hide.

text:
black and hues 3/3 ~ the dark truth of #metoo
.
at this point of time, i don't really care if my artwork looks good or not, as long as it conveys the message. i will be posting the tiny details of the post on my stories, so stay tuned for that. for now, let's address this issue. 
off late, the #metoomovement  has gained unnecessary momentum that no one can choose to ignore. i find this to be extremely cheap and inhumane, since the gravity of the issue is lost amongst the various propagandas people try to fulfill through this movement. like the arrest warrant for @nana.patekar wasn't enough. .
adding to it is the victimisation of the accused. in obvious scenarios like the kavanaugh v/s dr. ford case, where we know who is guilty, we are busy just fulfilling  political propaganda without understanding why the issue is so pertinent and important.

perhaps the most dreaded perspective of this movement, are the kind of stories that make it to the headlines: they are either really minute incidents happening to celebrities or incidents that take the shape of intercaste, political or personal rivalry. the incidents which actually hold great risks and treats to life never really surface.

i am outraged not as an indian girl who is sick of the way people handle this issue, but as a human and feminist, who demands social justice.

text: from @iamsheadiamond's page. voting is more than just a right and more than just a privilege. voting is the most effective and far reaching way to make your voice heard to the government. remember that our country is far from perfect and requires its citizens to step up and recognize injustice where its due. so this midterm election, please vote in the favor of equality and intersectionality. think of your neighbors, friends and family then think of their neighbors, friends and family and so on. no one should be left out when you go to vote tomorrow. thank you and good luck tomorrow! #vote #electionday #gay #trans #blacklivesmatter #translivesmatter #metoo #feminism #lgbt #equality

it's more important to be an empathetic, honourable & a compassionate yoga teacher  than a skilled yoga teacher.
.

#repost @therestlessquill (@get_repost)
ãƒ»ãƒ»ãƒ»
here's a story about a sexual harasser, mohan polamar, who is also a yoga teacher. oh the access. 
this is the couple who runs the practice room @thepracticeroomdotin in wheeler road, bangalore. 
the women whom he harassed got together and created this comic.

when the women complained, the practice room put together a committee. this included the harasser's wife who also runs the place along with the harasser. 
there was flat out denial, gaslighting and aggression.  the women were told the complaint would be entertained only if there were more than 10 women who complained. when the women insisted, he was asked to take time off. but a month later he's back to teaching, having "reflected deeply." and then, the cleverest cut of all. the husband and wife duo have coopted this comic to circulate this among their classes claiming what a great illustration of how not to behave as a yoga teacher.

#metooindia
#metoo #yogabuse #bksiyengaryoga #metooyoga #metoobangalore

text:
this was a serious business, it was actually backed by goldman sachs, but it crashed and went bankrupt because the gamers themselves who weren't cheating became enraged basically that these other people were doing, they put so much pressure on the gaming companies.

they put so much pressure on the video game companies, that they decided to basically ban gold-farming, which killed bannon's business, but it awakened him to the power of what he called "rootless white males" who spend all their time online. and five years later when bannon wound up at breitbart, he resolved to try and attract those people over to breitbart because he thought they could be radicalized in a kind of populist, nationalist way. and the way that bannon did that, the bridge between the angry abusive gamers and breitbart and pepe was milo yiannopoulous, who bannon discovered and hired to be breitbart's tech editor.

from the time i met him in 2011, he's had exactly the same politics. the same stuff you heard from trump, you saw on the campaign trail. what he was looking for was a vessel because nobody in republican washington believed in these kinds of ideas. the whole trend in the republican party was toward liberalizing immigration laws, passing comprehensive immigration reform. he was against it.

joshua green, author
devil's bargain: steve bannon, donald trump, and the storming of the presidency

text:
new podcast!

what if parenting could be fun, expansive and awake af?
what if a mother could be awake, and even sexy and spiritual?

sharon koshy is a soul-led parent coach, life coach, speaker, spiritual teacher, and writer. she recognized through her own journey as a daughter and a parent that parenting does not have to be an icky, heavy  experience but rather an expansive, fulfilling, and beautiful one (even through the hard times). she helps parents and their children thrive by inspiring them to discover how to step into being their best selves and live their best lives. 
what conscious parenting is and how it can help you shift your mindset as a parent.
the importance of embracing your feminine and sexuality, even as a mother!
how to have conversations with your kids about sexuality and what's important when having "the talk."
how you have the control and power to make a decision in situations, even when you don't see it.
why healing trauma is important at any age.
why it's okay to give you permission to ask for help and do what you need to do as a parent, even if you feel it's selfish.

text:
all power to @wanderingghandss.

talking about sexual misconduct within our yoga communities and groups is extremely important, especially if we want to maintain the sanctity and cleanliness of this space. as students of yoga, we put our bodies and minds and most importantly, our trust in the hands of our teachers. when this vulnerability is taken advantage of - it's not ok and it must be addressed! "the illustrated women's guide to yogabuse" is a comic created by @wanderingghandss .  a collective of artists who have experienced or stand by women who have experienced personal sexual harassment by the hands of yoga teacher, mohan palomar, from @thepracticeroomdotin,wheeler road, cooke town, bangalore.
they started their journey for justice by addressing this issue with 'the practice room' teachers, jaya chakravarty and mohan palomar, presenting them with testimonials of sexual misconduct by assistant teacher, mohan palomar, asking him to step down as a teacher, have an icc (internal complaints committee) set up so they could register their complaints and have him seek professional healthcare for this behaviour. their requests were met aggression, denial and their  words were not taken seriously. he is back teaching in class after having 'reflected deeply' for 2 weeks. after having their words fall on deaf ears for months, they decided to call out this behaviour through a comic and are now sharing it far and wide so that their story can be heard, acknowledged, cannot and will not be ignored anymore and most importantly in hope that nobody has to go through this kind of trauma again. worst of all, shortly after this comic saw the light of day - both husband and wife aka yoga teachers have copted this comic, gaslighting and mocking the collective, circulating their work within their yoga groups as a creatively illustrated example of what to look out for in a yoga class and how not to behave as a yoga teacher. 
#metoo #metooindia #metooyoga #thishastostop #wanderinghands #justice #allpowerforjustice #letstlk.

text:
do you remember this photo? wow, what a whirlwind it has been since i made the decision to share my story with you six months ago. i had no idea the ripple effects it would have, but here we are. 
i always knew i would write the story of my journey to healing. what i did not know at the time was that i was only half way there. god placed a desire in my heart to help others heal and that selfless desire blossomed into the new life i am now living, truly #healed. 
i want to thank you! thank you for your kind words and for all the love and support you showered me with. thank you for reading my blog despite the discomfort this topic stirs in you. most of all, thank you for sharing my work with the people you love-so that they can be healed too. 
god bless you!

#7stepstowardhealing #unbraided #healing #faith #journey #metoo

text:
for all the times i've been told to "mind my own business", because "what's an actor to do with politics?", to be careful, because "you don't want to take sides", for all the times they tried to shut me up because "these angry women are hateful and unattractive", for all the times i've been told to "go back to my country", for all this and more, tomorrow november 6th go vote.
and you know what? as a human being, a citizen, an immigrant, as a woman and as an artist, as a free person and an activist,  this is exactly my own business and i will keep minding that. and no, i won't stop taking sides. i will keep choosing what to give my voice to, and if you don't agree with it, fine. but you won't shut my mouth, you won't stop my song if freedom with your words of hatred.
this is a shot from my next monologue,  and as little as my contribution is, i will keep pursuing what the meaning if art is to me: freedom, education and bringing the light in the darkest nights. be fierce,  be happy, be loving. 
love,
#agirlfromtheislandinnewyork

text:
today, there remains no equal rights amendment in the u.s., despite it being reintroduced to congress every session since not being ratified by the states in 1982. there are several states remaining that have not ratified the amendment. with the ratification of the equal rights amendment by the state of nevada in 2017 and by illinois as the 37th state in 2018, one more state is needed to ratify the equal rights amendment to achieve the initial 38 states for federal ratification as determined in 1982. if one more state ratifies the era, the ratification process will move into the courts for determination regarding the constitutionality of the original deadline that was applied to the equal rights amendment. 
in the wake of women-led movements like the womenâ€™s march and #metoo, era activists have found renewed energy and current efforts to ratify the era are active in north carolina, tennessee, and florida.

but we can change this! it is important that americans understand the reality of gender inequality; that men and women are not guaranteed equal rights by law yet. i believe everyone was born with equal rights and are entitled to them as citizens of this great nation of ours. the amendment reads:

section 1. equality of rights under the law shall not be denied or abridged by the united states or by a state on account of sex.

section 2. the congress shall have the power to enforce, by appropriate legislation, the provisions of this article. 
section 3. this amendment shall take effect two years after the date of ratification.

#ncbw100 #advocacy #ratifyera #eraamendment #staywoke

text:
"navarasÄ 
raudra(anger) - part 1

triggered by humiliation or injustice, raudra acquires feisty colours from plain irritation to seething wrath. as a person with a hot headed temperament, this rasa, for reasons good and bad comes to me most naturally and just oozes out any send everytime i get an opportunity to express a lot of pent up and suppressed anger that i hold inside of me and as twisted as it may sound, i relish the catharsis. be it failing at a step despite practising it several times or just a flash of a heated argument in my personal life, it always results in me breathing heavily, glaring wide eyed and striking my footsteps with more force than necessary. 
the last time i felt as livid as i look here was not more than a month ago. with all the #metoo instances popping up on my timeline, it's about time i at least get it off my chest.

it was a saturday evening and i wanted to catch up with myself. so i stepped out for cheap retail therapy. the word "sale" was enough to catch my attention before i stepped into the kurti sale shop, right off a busy 8.00pm street in ramamaurthy nagar. as soon as i entered, the shopkeeper started thinking aloud about my waist size. after deliberating between 38 and 36, he labelled my love handles as a size 40. not that i asked for it. the discomfort began to creep in. i moved to the other section where to distract myself i began picking up random kurti pieces. this time his guessing game was about my chest size where he suggested which one cling and which one would fit just right. by now the panic alarm had begun ticking. i asked for a trial room to which he said i could slip it on top of what i was wearing. i began fumbling and shifted to another corner and quickly slipped one on. while i was taking it off, he held my top down so that it wouldn't come off with the kurti, ran his hands over my breasts saying "achcha padded pehna hai kya?" i flung the top and fled the scene and before i could scoot, i saw another man entering the shop when i exit ad the two looking at me and having a chat"
.
.
.
.
.
#art #dance #indianclassical #bharatnatyam #rasa #danceform #blackandwhite #artistic #context #raudra #anger #navarasa

text:
i am really glad i attended trauma sensitive yoga teacher training this past weekend but turns out i could not make it through the entire weekend and stayed home yesterday because it was so hard to digest the information. 
the therapists at treatment agreed that i have ptsd but i didn't want to get overly hung up on labels and wanted to believe that i can heal and rewire my brain but reading the book and course materials i saw so many behaviors in myself that i didn't know were caused by the underlying trauma and pain and it really made me sad. 
for my new followers i have been physically, verbally, sexually abused as well as dealt with a traumatic divorce and miscarriage at the same time 8 years ago. i have been focused on healing myself since 2015. 
i have been escaping with alcohol since i was a teenager. i wish i could have gotten the proper treatment at 16 instead of 36. for twenty years i hurt myself because i thought it was my fault, that i wasn't good enough to be loved and deserved it. i thought once i am perfect enough surely they will love me. 
that never happened and i had to save myself.  if you are abusing your children or are seeing children being abused by their families please help the child. they can't protect themselves and the damage it causes will impact them forever. they will repeat the same cycle of abuse in their own lives

text:
this was a serious business, it was actually backed by goldman sachs, but it crashed and went bankrupt because the gamers themselves who weren't cheating became enraged basically that these other people were doing, they put so much pressure on the gaming companies.

they put so much pressure on the video game companies, that they decided to basically ban gold-farming, which killed bannon's business, but it awakened him to the power of what he called "rootless white males" who spend all their time online. and five years later when bannon wound up at breitbart, he resolved to try and attract those people over to breitbart because he thought they could be radicalized in a kind of populist, nationalist way. and the way that bannon did that, the bridge between the angry abusive gamers and breitbart and pepe was milo yiannopoulous, who bannon discovered and hired to be breitbart's tech editor.

from the time i met him in 2011, he's had exactly the same politics. the same stuff you heard from trump, you saw on the campaign trail. what he was looking for was a vessel because nobody in republican washington believed in these kinds of ideas. the whole trend in the republican party was toward liberalizing immigration laws, passing comprehensive immigration reform. he was against it.

joshua green, author
devil's bargain: steve bannon, donald trump, and the storming of the presidency

text: iâ€™ve been quiet this week. iâ€™ve been traveling and took some time away from social media, both of which make it easier for me to hold space for myself and introspect. i find that when most people travel and subsequently write about it on social media, they only want to show the good stuff. the magic. the heavily filtered photos of someoneâ€™s hiking-booted feet dangling over horseshoe bend at the grand canyon, or a gorgeous bikini-ed girl gazing upon a polychromatic sunset from the edge of an infinity pool in morocco. and thatâ€™s wonderful! i have beautiful moments when i travel. i love those moments! but my mental illness doesnâ€™t go on vacation when i do. i donâ€™t get to take a sabbatical from my survivorship. that means that when my sister and i were very grossly catcalled on the strip outside the bellagio, i had to go in the bathroom and put my head between my knees when we got back to the hotel. that means that when my flight was delayed five hours and stranded me in las vegas by myself, i publicly cried over a way-too-expensive glass of malbec at an airport bar. those things are my normal sometimes. there is nothing wrong with appreciating and sharing the beautiful and the incredible. the problem comes when weâ€™re so inundated by curated perfection that we start to feel that normal is negative. we hide the imperfections we should honor and care for. i made @bossladycreates to openly honor my ugly. to ultimately normalize imperfection. how do you do that for yourself? âœ¨ #travel #anxiety #cptsd #selfcare #journaling #survivor #survivorselfcare #believesurvivors #metoo

text: this is morgan, one of the creators of this account. â€œi was sexually assaulted by two boys in my sophomore year of highschool, one of which was a family friend who even my parents trusted, and the other was his best friend. me and the girl i was dating at the time would always spend time with these boys, and i was the youngest of the group. i was 16 when we decided to have a house party instead of going to their senior prom. i was excited to act grown and do what the upper classmen did, and the party was at my girlfriends plaxe so i wasâ€™t worried. i realize now that those decisions led me to grow up way too fast. i was taken advantage of by both boys that night, too intoxicated to get up and leave the room, let alone â€˜just say noâ€™. i attended school with them just like normal the following monday and no one said a thing. this led me to believe i was overthinking things, what they did to me was normal, and that it would be dramatic for me to question what happened that friday night. my senior year we were watching a documentary on sexual assault in class and i had my first ever panic attack. hearing the stories of other victims brought back what seemed like flashbacks of my own trauma and i broke down. even though it had been two years of staying silent, i had finally come to the realization that what happened to me was wrong. i filed a report and attempted to press charges in june of this year and i am still waiting. it is a long and frustrating process, many parts of which include reliving the trauma i thought iâ€™d escaped in order to relay the details of what exactly happened. i chose this picture as the one that empowers me  most because despite all the hardships i faced in highscool, i graduated. i decorated my cap with lyrics of my favorite song and i dressed up. i overcame the toughest 4 years of my life surrounded by my friends and family. my boyfriend was the one who took this photo, which means a lot to me. weâ€™ve been together for two years now and although itâ€™s been hell overcoming my trust issues to build a strong relationship, he is now my biggest support system.â€

text:
â€œi distinctively remember this day because of my overwhelming sense of discomfort. i was working as a host at a pub at the time, just shy of 19. it was midday, rainy. this man came in and i sat him at the only open table outside. as a host, i also had the responsibility of bussing tables, so here and there i would leave the stand to go outside to see if tables needed bussing. when i stepped out, the older man i seated began to talk to me. "you are very beautiful."
me: "thank you."
"except you're really pale, you should go to the tanning bed."
me: "uhm no i have skin cancer in my family. i like my skin."
"we could go there together and i could get in the tanning bed with you"
i immediately went back inside and felt really uncomfortable. following that incident, he came inside and began to follow me to wherever i went. i told him i was working and he kept getting in my personal bubble and saying that i wasn't working and would just stare at me. this may sound like something small, but, to me, i felt like i wanted to cry because i was mutually uncomfortable, i felt a little violated and i also felt extreme anger. i felt so disgusted that someone would look at me and think something like that & then verbalizing it was even more insane. the man was later on kicked out for not paying, but i did tell my coworkers and my boss that he was harassing me, so please speak up if something like this happens to you.â€

text:
hasil pemenang
quiz 4 tahun bollywood first indonesia

hadiah : pulsa @25k untuk 3 terpilih 
jawaban :
1. produksi film ini penuh kontroversi, mulai dari casting pemeran hingga tanggal perilisan. drama periodik ini di sutradarai sanjay leela bhansali dan mendapat rilis pada januari lalu. film apa yang dimaksud?
[padmaavat]

2. bintang bollywood ini mengumumkan dirinya mengidap penyakit yang serius. bahkan saat ini dia masih melakukan perawatan di london dan amerika. bintang multitalenta ini pernah beradu akting dengan deepika padukone. siapakah dia?
[irrfan khan]

3. sutradara luv ranjan kembali sukses tahun ini dengan drama romantisnya. film ini kembali dibintangi bintang favoritnya yakni kartik aaryan, sunny singh dan nushrat bharucha. film apa yang dimaksud?
[sonu ke titu ki sweety]

4. superstar bollywood shahrukh khan baru saja merayakan hari jadinya yang ke berapa?
[53 tahun]

5. zain kapoor adalah nama putra ke-2 pasangan bollywood ini. zain kapoor lahir tahun ini. siapakah pasangan itu ?
[shahid kapoor & mira rajput]

6. pasangan bollywood ini mengumumkan undangan pernikahan mereka yang jatuh pada tanggal 14-15 nopember ini. siapakah pasangan tersebut ?
[deepika padukone & ranveer singh]

7. gerakan #metoo membuat perubahan besar di industri bollywood. beberapa pelaku pelecehan seksual satu demi satu terkuak dan mengakui kesalahan mereka. tokoh bollywood ini langsung keluar dari kursi sutradara proyek housefull 4 setelah dituduh melakukan pelecehan seksual. siapa dia ?
[sajid khan]

berikut 3 pemenang terpilih :
1. @desychinai
2. @anhy_nhya 
3. @shadhi.bolly02 
silakan inbox / dm no.hape aktif !

selamat kepada para pemenang terpilih, untuk yang belum beruntung bisa coba di lain quiz. 
terimakasih atas ucapan ulang tahun, doa dan partisipasi dalam mengikuti quiz untuk bollywood first indonesia.

text:
you told me
that i was worth nothing
you told me 
i was unlovable 
you told me 
it was all my fault 
you told me
that one day i would die
you told me 
that you would keep me safe 
you.. kept me in chains, broke my bones, scarred my outside and inside, loved me with hate and rage of your deepest soul 
i promised 
to behave and change myself 
i promised 
to not to talk to anyone
i promised 
to not cry and scream 
i promised 
to stay and never leave even when i got hurt so bad
i broke all my promises when i decided i wanted life 
i wanted a safe place for me and my daughter 
i broke them all and i never will be silent again for anyone. 
we are safe 
we are warriors 
we are survivors 
we are alive and 
we are proud to be strong women without you 
#domesticabuse #domesticviolence #womenrise #strongwomen #metoo #makeyourvoiceheard #women #husfrid #skatepro #skateboard #jailtime #wearestrong #violence #domesticviolenceawareness

text: 4 days ago. the caravan of refugees walking months to potentially have a chance at a better future. a decision people make everyday to achieve what they can and get the most out what they for themselves in this life. 4 days ago, they were walking approaching states run by corruption and cartels. the government tried to redirect them south, sent buses to pick them up and stop them. it was that option, or walk through the cartels state without assistance. that is where they are today. children, women, and men, walking through that territory. to be that driven for hope of a better future that much. knowing they won't arrive in full numbers to be met by military force at the border. they are refugees, who deserve the warmest welcome.  they are human. they are intelligent and determined.  to pass through corrupt mafia states walking, cannot be what is left for america. or anyone. they're taking their lives with them, to come here, we should be honoring them for wanting to be part of our country. #voteblue #metoo #blacklivesmatter #waterprotectors #getheresafely #itshumantomakechoicesandwalkforyourlife #america #americaiswherewesharethekingdom

text:
do you know why many #victims of #sexual #violence either never disclose or wait years to share their #stories?
 according to the huffpost:
1. #perpetrators and their allies undermine #victimsâ€™ credibility and impugn their #character. 
2. the community often rallies around the #perpetrator and pillories the survivor. predators groom individuals and entire #communities so that they gain the trust of victims and so that they have a convenient â€œgood guyâ€ cover in place in case they are exposed.
3. survivors face a barrage of questions when they come forward instead of the sympathy and support they need. why didnâ€™t you speak out sooner? why didnâ€™t you try to stop the attacks? these questions add to the trauma and horror of #sexual #violence.
4. #survivors sometimes have kept in touch with their perpetrators. maybe they continued dating, working together, or interacting politely at family events. continued contact with a perpetrator is also very common. often this factor alone keeps victims trapped in silence.
5. not reporting allows a #survivor to maintain the fantasy that people in positions of responsibility would be helpful if he or she did report. reporting often crushes that fantasy when responsible people protect themselves and the perpetrator instead.
6. a lot of #survivors prefer to create an alternate reality, one in which the abuse didnâ€™t happen. 
7. #survivors find it easier to pretend to be normal and live a lie than face the horror of sexual abuse and trauma.
8. survivors often fear that coming forward will result in the loss of employment, support network, housing, reputation, and even their lives. 
9. some #survivors simply donâ€™t remember and suppressed the memories of abuse.
10. in the case of child #sexual abuse (and oftentimes abuse of adults), reporting can disrupt every relationship important to the survivors. #family members and friends choose the easier narrative:the victim is lying.

text:
similar to hester with dimmesdale, monica lewinsky was severely shamed after committing adultery with president bill clinton. initially, the mention of the name â€œmonica lewinskyâ€ created the subconscious association with the term â€œadultererâ€. within one night, lewinsky â€œwent from being a completely private figure to a publicly humiliated one worldwideâ€ (lewinsky- ted talk), with one click of a news article, since this story was the first in which the internet surpassed traditional news coverage for a major news story. yet, lewinsky refused to let the world bring her down, overcoming her labels by becoming a reemerging as world-renowned activist for women, cyberbullying, and becoming a key figure in the #metoo campaign. with this, monica used her scandal to raise awareness and inspire individuals who have been harassed/shamed, through motivational speeches and the publication of her own book: shame nation: the global epidemic of online hateâ€. all in all, both hester and lewinsky used their experience of adultery and shaming to help overcome and influence affected women to stay strong and realize that a single night should and does not define their social identity.
source: https://www.ted.com/talks/monica_lewinsky_the_price_of_shame/transcript#t-1365264 (opinion) #discriminationisover

text:
over the past two years iâ€™ve tried to strike a balance. i was so wrecked after the last election cycle. triggering scenarios around abusive behavior toward women (weeks after having my own #metoo story), a complete lack of decorum and civility. the country being treated like a pawn in a game instead of with the respect it deserves. â£
â£
so i went in hiding. i started truly practicing self care. not bubble baths and cookies but moderation of consuming media and the news, learning boundaries at a new level, meditating more. trying to find solace in my spiritual practice and a way to create change from there. all of that is well and good, and needed. â£
â£
and with all of this said there is still an underlying truth. we are all here living on this planet together. it is our responsibility to tend to it, its people and society to the best of our ability. this is where participation comes in. we must participate in or communities, in or neighborhoods, in our cities, counties, states and country. it is through a connected voice of the people that change and progress happen. â£
â£
we are each part of that voice. the biggest tool and power you have aside from where and how you spend money is your vote.  your vote is your voice. â£
please go use it, use it with our next generation in mind. use it as the native americans did - with the next seven generations in mind. what we do today effects more than tomorrow it effects the next 100 years. â£
â£
please, go vote tomorrow. â£
please, get involved in causes youâ€™re passionate about. â£
please engage civilly with our world and society. â£
please be a messenger of peace. â£

another version of the interview our founder ireti bakare-yusuf had with @bbcnewsyoruba

#repost @sisiogelagos

last week was pidgin, this week, enjoy this snippet from my @bbcnewsyoruba interview. talking about the #nomore app and that menace in our society #rape #sexualviolence #sexualabuse. full interview is on bbcnewsyoruba website . 
because the plague isn't going away, because we have to keep taking about it, because silence only favours the predators, because there are more of us, than there are of them. @nomore234ng 
some have asked me why i look so sad in these interviews, compares to my normal smiley self. somehow, involuntarily, i  become a frowning tiger. i fight back twars of anger and sometimes exasperation. i keep telling myself, promising that i won't get emotional, so far, i've not been able to keep that promise. one day, just maybe one day, it will stop. as long as we continue to say #nomore, we will chase all predators out of our homes and community. 
thank you @bbcafrica @bbcnewsyoruba @bbcnewspidgin for your support and interest in the cause.

text:
i received a message this week asking if i was still a believer. at first i was hurt and angry, wanting to write paragraphs defending my faith. instead, i quieted my heart and asked god to give me the words. 
i responded,
"thank you for being concerned. yes, i believe in a god who walked and is still always walking with the marganalized, turning over tables with the privileged. that is the god i see."
i wish i could bring you back to the morning after election day two years ago. as my daughter walked into my room,i met her eyes and began to weep. i couldn't protect her again.this isn't a one issue election. this is an act of justice. 
#yearofhope #yearofhealing #golfinches #metoo #believesurvivors #yearofforgiveness#hopewriters

text: â€œmisogynyâ€ is an awful word. it is something that women face constantly. i have been extremely fortunate that it has not happened often in my life, and almost all of the men that i know or have encountered in passing on my journey are honourable and decent human beings. but recently it did, and from the most unexpected source. it has taken me a while to process what happened to me, and i think itâ€™s something we need to talk about more openly, as itâ€™s not *just* #metoo - sometimes men can be threatening even when there is no sexual element involved, but merely because they assume that their feelings and wishes are the only ones that matter. so i will say this: misogyny is not okay. being threatening towards a woman in order to get your way or control a situation is not okay. sending harassing messages on social media and by sms is not okay. trying to force your way into someoneâ€™s private space is not okay.  neither is getting physical and kicking in doors. i donâ€™t care who you are - i donâ€™t care if you are straight or gay, you cannot behave this way to any human being. and know this - i will always stand up to misogynists. and i want all the women i know to know that itâ€™s not isolated, itâ€™s not something you did that caused their behaviour, itâ€™s not something you could fix if you just let them walk all over you - you donâ€™t ever need to accept being bullied by a man. #misogyny #endmisogyny #bullying #stopbullying

text:
throughout her complicated life, maya angelou served as a preliminary speaker for the #timesup and #metoo movement and a inspirational figure for both race and gender discrimination. angelou accomplished this through the publication of 36 books, seven autobiographies, three grammys, and over 50 honorary degrees. most notably, her first book, i know why the caged bird sings (1969), describes the time she was sexually assaulted by her motherâ€™s boyfriend. in a time where sexual harassment was prevalent and not as frowned upon as it is today, angelou raised awareness for related women, convincing them they are not alone and can persevere through even these times. in her poems, angelou wrote about the strength of women, demanded for justice, and the need for the civil rights movement for african american rights. she would go on to be given the opportunity (second ever) to read an inaugural poem, in which she spoke of peace, freedom, and justice in a society of people with different sexual attractions, genders, incomes, races, origins, and religious affiliations, and would receive the 2010 presidential medal of freedom from barack obama. both angelou and prynne used their experiences as a platform for women, and racial (angelou), empowerment in predominantly white patriarchal societies.

it makes perfect sense. i was watching a documentary where they discussed the correlation between abusing the earth and abusing women... and it clicked inside me.
ğŸŒ
yes! mother earth is a feminine energy and we have shit all over it like we have shit on women! the technological advances that our society has achieved over the last decades have been great for some things but there have been terrible consequences in other ways and they have led us to where we are now.
ğŸŒ
but not all is lost.  i see change.  i see a new generation of #millennials who are ready to work and make a difference and want to link up, arm in arm with their elders to help. itâ€™s not just an environmental shift either... oh no. itâ€™s a spiritual shift that is taking place.
ğŸŒ
why do you think crystals and spirit and tarot cards and meditation and yoga are booming with popularity now? itâ€™s not a phase, itâ€™s a change thatâ€™s happening.
ğŸŒ
i for one love it and want to stand and support anyone ready to make that shift. we are discovering who we are and realizing that the old ways are better in a lot of instances. are you ready to shift with us? with the planet?
ğŸŒ
less ego, more love.
less fear, more love.
less hate, more love.
less greed, more love.
less sadness, more love.
less dysfunction, more love.
ğŸŒ
because that is what we are.

text:
i know this series of photos (swipe) is going to seem cheesy and weird to a lot of you but itâ€™s been a weird and torturous week. facing my literal demon in the form of my abuser worming his way back into my life uninvited and unapologetic. with #ptsd the first instinct is to shut down. short circuit from the pain. turn it in on yourself where you become totally self destructive and paralysed.  my happy life and future seemed once again derailed as i lay in bed willing sleep to make the pain go away, feeling exactly as paralysed and helpless as diana in this picture. evil would always win it seemed. i was destined to be hurt over and over in fresh ways just as i let my guard down and allowed myself to hope i was going to be able to live to my full potential.  but then something brought this scene to mind. my power in the form of love freed me to fight. i fight for my children. my brave beautiful children who have lost so much of me. who will *not* lose any more of me. love. will. conquer. evil. every. time. for all the evil monsters in the world there are more good beautiful people. you might not have met them yet but they are there. this weekend i screamed back at the demon. i named him. i got him out of my head where he tortured me and put his name on a facebook page and left him to be eviscerated. which he deserves. ***i do not say that with malice friends****. this is necessary. abusers pedophiles are evil people who thrive in our shame and silence. they do not deserve our protection. we have no shame. we must bring their evil to light and let that light burn them out of our hearts and minds and lives. and then love and support and beauty can replace the dark spaces they occupied and grew around like a cancer. find the love inside of you and fight back. we your tribe have your back. still. we. rise. always. forever. love wins. 
#ptsdawareness #ptsdrecovery #metoo #stillirise #ptsdrecovery #lovewins

text: i have heard several adult men talk about being sexually abused by "an older woman" when they were preteens/teens and none of them enjoyed it. because the truth is, an erection nor ejaculation are signs that a male wanted to participate in the act or enjoyed it. these are merely natural bodily responses to a stimuli. in fact, these men will tell you that being sexually abused as a boy affected them in ways that shaped their views on sex; how they related to women, how they treated women, and their ability to intimately connect with women. some also developed a hyper masculinity to mask the loss of control they felt during the abuse. their pain was buried because they knew that so many viewed their experience as "their first taste" or "their entrance into manhood", instead of an act of sexual assault. and, just like any other act of sexual abuse/assault, they needed a safe place to process what happened to them and heal, regardless of how old they were when it happened and how old they were when they disclosed it. sexual assault/abuse affects all of its victims. the wounds are just under the surface, but if we get close enough we start to see their shape.  #childsexabuseawareness #stopchildsexabuse #childsexabusesurvivor #parentsofchilldsexabusesurvivor #sexualassault #endchildsexabuse #endrapeculture #childabuse #sextrafficking #atlanta #atl #georgia #women #girls #teens #awareness #sexcrimes #rapevictims #rape #victims #children #prevention #trafficking  #survivor #tips #blogger #speaker #metoo #advocate
