text:
âœ¨week of november 5thâœ¨part 2.
â€¢
â€¢
november 8th:
â€¢
jupiter enters sagittarius @ 7:38am est
â™ƒâ™ï¸
jupiter has been transiting in the sign of scorpio since october 2017. jupiter magnifies the sign where it is transiting. in the sign of scorpio it collectively brought to the surface sexual scandals and the #metoo movement. a lot of darkness came to the surface to be healed this year with jupiter in scorpio.
â€¢
jupiter is at home in the mutable fire sign of sagittarius and this will definitely be felt. jupiter is the yes/more planets often associated with optimism and broad vision. look to where sagittarius sits in your chart to understand where this influx of potentiality will start to grow.
â€¢
from astrologer ronnie pontiac: ''as this is jupiterâ€™s own sign we may expect a better atmosphere, more optimism than jupiter in scorpio can muster. on the negative side over indulgence, arrogance, bs for the joy of it, and sky high expectations may rule the day. donâ€™t get so carried away that you wind up losing what you gained. for sagittarians or people with strong sagittarius placements this can be a time of opportunity and prosperity. geminis, pisces and virgos the next year or so will be a time when over doing it, being arrogant, wearing rose colored glasses might have more severe consequences than usual. but this same potential for opportunity and prosperity is there for your signs as well if you work for it. leos and aries may feel luckier than usual. aquarians and librans keep your eyes open so you donâ€™t miss good fortune. as the yi jing says, see like a heron watching a lake.''
â€¢
â€¢
venus is still retrograde in the sign of libra until november 16 and will turn direct just as mercury turns retrograde in sagittarius.
â€¢
â€¢
we are not completely out of the woods yet but this week has a lot of momentum behind it. you would have to live under a rock not to feel the switch from fixed to mutable/cardinal this week. it will get easier and easier to initiate changes in the weeks to come and harder to hold on to outmoded patterns. #flow
â€¢
have a fantastic week!

text: spending some time this morning to just look over the sample ballot again and the propositions iâ€™ll be voting on tomorrow because i love election day and going to the polls because itâ€™s my right as a citizen and women and minorities fought with their actual lives for me to have this privilege and it matters. you matter. please donâ€™t take it for granted and if you are uncertain about whatâ€™s on your ballot or have questions please donâ€™t be ashamed to ask. itâ€™s confusing shit sometimes. it can be overwhelming but i ask seemingly dumb questions all the time because thatâ€™s how we learn. and if you canâ€™t vote because of a felony or citizenship or age you can use your voice to encourage your friends and family to show up. letâ€™s do this. november has come. #voteordie #scorpioseason #votethemout #metoo #blacklivesmatter #timesup #allwomen #ibelievechristineblaseyford â¤ï¸â¤ï¸â¤ï¸

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

text:

text:
perfect! can't wait to wear my upcycled jeans.

take a minute to think about this:
1.) economy is war  2.) regular fashion industry gets ruled by racists, sexist and idiots that don't care about nature. this is what you really paying for. 3.) why do you want to be a basicbÃ—Ã—Ã—Ã—? you could be special and a little hero, by supporting fair and ethical brands. you don't have to be a puppet.

i like unperfection, it makes things or people more interesting and lovable. are you trying to be perfect and cool? why? what are you hiding?

by the way... i know, i don't translate everything correctly. i simply don't care. i could write in perfect english and say nothing. i like myself more a little angry, honest and authentic.

good girls (or men) get angry and change the world! depressions are not helping anyone.

text:
#vote like your healthcare, ss, & medicare is on the line. 
#vote like your air, water, and soil is being poisoned by greedy corporations, with zero restrictions and zero consequences.

#vote like toddlers are locked in concentration camps, and so desperate, they're hanging themselves with nooses made from their bedsheets. while costing taxpayers $789 each per day, and making private prison companies richer. 
#vote like grown-ass men can throw screaming tantrums & be elected to the highest court in the land, while women are deemed "too hysterical and weak" to lead. 
#vote like nazis are not "very fine people." #vote like the so-called leader of the country mocks the #metoo movement & sexual assault survivors during hate rallies, while his supporters laugh & cheer. 
#vote like owning assault weapons doesn't trump our children's lives. 
#vote like 200 mass murders were committed by angry white male homegrown terrorists, and then the so-called leader of the country axed the domestic terrorist program.

#vote like the so-called leader of the country called for our soldiers to commit war crimes by shooting unarmed refugees seeking asylum.

#vote like pharmacists can refuse medication to women suffering from miscarriages, or refuse to dispense birth control for "religious objections." #vote like poc, jewish people, and the lgbt community are increasing targets of hatred, with deadly consequences.

#vote like the top 1% just got handed trillions of your tax dollars.

#vote like massive voter suppression by gop officials is happening.

#vote while you still can.

text:
"make survivors silent again" -pen and ink, acrylic on canvas paper

the craters and landfills of ambiguity trip me, twist my ankles, scrape my knees. 
but i must stumble on. 
never mind their stench i carry on my skin, 
their mold growing on my weary feet, 
their spiders taking refuge in my mouth tightening their webs around my tongue to seal away â€œmyâ€ filth on behalf of the public and the guilty 
the contorted faces match the knots in my stomach as i speak of what was done to me. 
is it disgust? 
is it disbelief? 
of humanity or of me? 
i can feel the shushing. 
is it for me? or is it for them? 
to calm their nerves? or mine? 
i can live with myself. 
i cannot live in a world where survivors like me are thrown into the wastelands to be forgotten. 
rather than stamping a period at the end of justice, the gavel of the law knocks the wind from my lungs. 
neglected webs collect in the corners of the court room. 
evil swings joyously from gaudy chandeliers. 
morality, a ghost amongst the appointed, is swept under garish rugs along with unlawful sins. 
leaving me to walk the abandoned lots, crunching on the bones of the ones that came before me each step incriminating me, â€œyour fault, your fault.â€ silently acknowledging figures of my own form from a distance. 
spiders, dissociated shadows, and secrets being my only companions.

text:
bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn

this was a serious business, it was actually backed by goldman sachs, but it crashed and went bankrupt because the gamers themselves who weren't cheating became enraged basically that these other people were doing, they put so much pressure on the gaming companies.

they put so much pressure on the video game companies, that they decided to basically ban gold-farming, which killed bannon's business, but it awakened him to the power of what he called "rootless white males" who spend all their time online. and five years later when bannon wound up at breitbart, he resolved to try and attract those people over to breitbart because he thought they could be radicalized in a kind of populist, nationalist way. and the way that bannon did that, the bridge between the angry abusive gamers and breitbart and pepe was milo yiannopoulous, who bannon discovered and hired to be breitbart's tech editor.

from the time i met him in 2011, he's had exactly the same politics. the same stuff you heard from trump, you saw on the campaign trail. what he was looking for was a vessel because nobody in republican washington believed in these kinds of ideas. the whole trend in the republican party was toward liberalizing immigration laws, passing comprehensive immigration reform. he was against it.

joshua green, author
devil's bargain: steve bannon, donald trump, and the storming of the presidency

is what cambridge analytica does akin to bullying? - i think itâ€™s worse than bullying, christopher wylie says. - because people donâ€™t necessarily know itâ€™s being done to them. at least bullying respects the agency of people because they know. so itâ€™s worse, because if you do not respect the agency of people, anything that youâ€™re doing after that point is not conducive to a democracy. and fundamentally, information warfare is not conducive to democracy.

millions of peopleâ€™s personal information was stolen and used to target them in ways they wouldnâ€™t have seen, and couldnâ€™t have known about, by a mercenary outfit, cambridge analytica, who, wylie says, â€œwould work for anyoneâ€. who would pitch to russian oil companies. would they subvert elections abroad on behalf of foreign governments?

it occurs to me to ask wylie this one night. - yes.

nato or non-nato? - either. i mean theyâ€™re mercenaries. theyâ€™ll work for pretty much anyone who pays.

itâ€™s an incredible revelation. it also encapsulates all of the problems of outsourcing â€“ at a global scale, with added cyberweapons. and in the middle of it all are the public â€“ our intimate family connections, our â€œlikesâ€, our crumbs of personal data, all sucked into a swirling black hole thatâ€™s expanding and growing and is now owned by a politically motivated billionaire.

text:
@galloydama was born from a vision to celebrate our latin culture & our family that inspired us to embrace our heritage, traditions and stories that brought us here. 
this t-shirt has a mission to celebrate women and remind them that they they are strong, beautiful damaâ€™s and that we all hold the key to their dreams and self-confidence.  we, as a unified humanity just need to step up to give them opportunities, encouragement and love â¤ï¸. i vividly remember when i first saw a picture of my mom in a kelly green skirt suit she sewed herself with a matching hat. i was fascinated that she made it with her own hands, her own skills and proudly wore it looking like a dama, like the one from the loteria card. and to think that my mom picked cotton in her youth blows my mind. it wasnâ€™t stories of my great-grandparents picking cotton it was my own own parents, just one generation from mine. to know the hands of my mother picked the very own cotton that she would eventually use to make her own clothes is something that blows my mind. 
the women in my life have always been strong and hard working women with a gift to look and act like ladies, damaâ€™s. call me old fashion but i still believe in acting like a lady, itâ€™s something i believe that allows me to keep my dignity, my respect and honor my family. 
proceeds of this shirt support local organizations supporting the culture of our latin heritage, the education & resources for latinos, and women suffering from sex trafficking. 
i believe all women should be celebrated just as equally as any #bossgirl , because whether we are stay at home moms, hardworking women trying to support our families in any job industry or 
any female born in the world for that matter, all damas! we are all beautiful, special and have our own story to tell. 
if interested in a shirt leave a comment, they are coming soon.

text: when i was 10 years old, the most traumatizing thing that has ever happened to me happened. just like that, my life was changed forever. it was someone i knew, worse, someone i was related to. i never said a word to another person. not when child protective services showed up and said that someone had reported it. when it happened, when i was asked about, and each time i thought about it until i finally told someone 9 years later, i was paralyzed with fear, unable to move, and unable to do anything about it to help myself. for years, i had nightmares that were as vivid as the event itself. because of this, i was able to convince myself that it happened to me. i didnâ€™t want to admit it. i was afraid that my family wouldnâ€™t believe me, because i had said it didnâ€™t happen. i wasnâ€™t dressed in a provocative way, i was in my pajamas. i didnâ€™t â€œwant itâ€, i was a 10 year old girl who hadnâ€™t so much as had her period yet. i wasnâ€™t trying to make up a story for attention. so i hid my pain. when he died while i was in high school, i cried tears of joy because i thought it meant that my secret would finally die. it would finally stop haunting me. i wouldnâ€™t have to worry about it happening to my little sister, or for something else to happen to me. i wasnâ€™t raped. i wasnâ€™t even penetrated, but none of that matter. this trauma has caused me lifelong issues. the only reason i told my parents what happened to me was because it caused depression and anxiety. it is still something i deal with. i have panic attacks thinking about walking alone to the bus stop at 10 am. the nightmares never stopped. i have to deal with the reality that this happened to me almost every day. victims donâ€™t come out for a number of reasons, and that absolutely does not mean they are lying. i maintained a 4.0 for 9 years. i got into every school i applied to. i passed 10/12 of the ap tests i took. not a single person ever suspected that something so awful happened to me, but it did, and none of the people i finally told doubted me for a second. #stopsilencingvictimsofabuse #metoo #empowersurvivors
